# 📘 Coding Conventions

## TypeScript

- Define interfaces/types for all props and shared shapes (see `types/studyflow.ts`).
- Prefer explicit types; avoid `any` (use `unknown` if required).
- Use `import type` for type-only imports when possible.

## Naming

- Components/files: PascalCase (`TimerDisplay.tsx`).
- Functions/vars: camelCase (`timeRemaining`, `startCycle`).
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (`FOCUS_PRESETS`).
- Hooks: `use*` prefix (`useStudyFlow`, `useIsMobile`).
- Event handlers: `handle*`.

## Component Pattern

```tsx
interface Props {
  required: string;
  optional?: number;
  variant?: "focus" | "workout";
}
const Component: React.FC<Props> = ({
  required,
  optional,
  variant = "focus",
}) => {
  return <div>...</div>;
};
export default Component;
```

## Imports Order

1. React & hooks
2. Third-party libs
3. Internal components (`@/components/...`)
4. Utilities (`@/lib/...`)
5. Types (`@/types/...`)
6. Relative paths

## State & Effects

- Use Context for global state; keep local UI state with `useState`.
- Memoize callbacks passed down (`useCallback`); memoize expensive derived data (`useMemo`).
- Always clean up intervals/timeouts in `useEffect`.

## Accessibility & UX

- Semantic HTML, ARIA where needed, keyboard navigable controls.
- Keep buttons/links focusable; manage focus in modals/dialogs.

## Anti-Patterns

- ❌ Mutating state directly.
- ❌ Side effects in render.
- ❌ Missing dependency arrays in hooks.
- ❌ Unbounded inline object/array creation without memoization.
